HIGHLANDS IN CHEMISTRY SEMINAR

Prof. Mark Schoenfisch
University of North Carolina, Chapel Hill

"Fighting implant-associated infections with nitric oxide-based macromolecu=
lar therapeutics and diagnostics"

Friday, February 20
2:30 p.m.
Hahn Hall North 140
Hosts: John Matson

Despite sterilization and aseptic procedures, bacterial infections continue=
 to plaque the utility of many medical devices. Such infections are difficu=
lt to treat because of how the adhered bacteria protect themselves--within =
a protective biofilm matrix on the device surface. While the number of biof=
ilm associated infections continues to rise, the rate of discovery of new a=
ntibiotics is slowing significantly. Alarmingly, bacteria are becoming more=
 resistant to currently-available antibiotics. As an alternative to convent=
ional therapies, we have developed macromolecular therapeutics capable of s=
toring and release nitric oxide, a potent bactericidal agent. We are also i=
mplementing new analytical methodologies for measuring nitric oxide in phys=
iological milieu as a biomarker for infection. My presentation will give an=
 overview of implant-associated infections, and then describe the synthesis=
 and characterization of macromolecular vehicles capable of spontaneous nit=
ric oxide release, the use and efficacy of such vehicles against bacteria, =
and the development of microfluidic nitric oxide sensors as tools for point=
-of-care blood analysis.

Please remember to sign up on the Scholar Wiki if you would like to meet wi=
th him.

EMillie Shephard
Department of Chemistry
480 Davidson Hall, MC 0212
Blacksburg, VA  24061
Office: (540) 231-5966


